President Barack Obama has proclaimed April as National Financial Literacy Month. In the proclamation, he emphasizes the importance of Americans being knowledgeable about their financial decisions, especially in the aftermath of the economic crisis. He mentions the need for better behavior and oversight on Wall Street, as well as informed decision-making on Main Street and in homes across the country. The Credit Card Accountability, Responsibility, and Disclosure Act and the Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act are mentioned as important measures to enforce consumer financial protections and restore financial stability. The proclamation also highlights the establishment of the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau and the President's Advisory Council on Financial Capability to assist Americans in understanding and addressing financial matters. Ultimately, the proclamation calls upon all Americans to observe National Financial Literacy Month by participating in programs and activities that improve their understanding of financial principles and practices.